 "components": {
  "instruction": "Classify the given text into one of these categories: alarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nImportant classification guidelines:\n\n1. **Calendar vs Alarm distinction**:\n   - Use 'calendar_set' for reminders, appointments, events, or tasks scheduled for specific dates and times (e.g., \"make a reminder for friday at six p.m.\", \"schedule a meeting for tomorrow\")\n   - Use 'alarm_set' only for wake-up alarms or short-term time-based alerts without specific date context (e.g., \"set an alarm for 7 a.m.\", \"wake me up in 30 minutes\")\n   - If the user mentions a specific day/date (like \"friday\", \"tomorrow\", \"next week\"), it should typically be 'calendar_set', not 'alarm_set'\n\n2. **Calendar Query vs Recommendation Events**:\n   - When a user is asking about the time or details of an event they already have scheduled (e.g., \"what time is the [event name] tonight\"), this should be classified as 'calendar_query' NOT 'recommendation_events'. The key indicator is that the user is referring to a specific event they already know about and wants to check the timing or details from their calendar.\n   - Use 'recommendation_events' when the user is asking for suggestions about events to attend or discover, not when querying details about events they're already tracking.\n   - Pay close attention to whether the user is querying existing information (calendar_query) versus seeking new recommendations (recommendation_events).\n\n3. General approach:\n   - Carefully analyze whether the user is creating/setting something, querying existing information, or seeking recommendations\n   - Look for temporal indicators (dates, days of the week) to distinguish between calendar and alarm functions\n   - Consider the context and intent behind the user's request"
 },
